net.sf.click.jquery.behavior
Class JQFormBehavior

java.lang.Object
  AjaxBehavior
      net.sf.click.jquery.behavior.AbstractJQBehavior
          net.sf.click.jquery.behavior.JQBehavior
              net.sf.click.jquery.behavior.JQFormBehavior
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable
public class JQFormBehavior
extends JQBehavior

Provide a specialized JQuery helper that Ajax enables a target Form.

This helper has an associated JavaScript template that can be modified according to your needs. Click here to view the template.

JQFormHelper can either be embedded inside a custom Form, or used to decorate the Form.

Embedded example

Below is an example of a custom Form with an embedded JQFormHelper that enables Ajax behavior: 
 public class JQForm extends AjaxForm {

     // The embedded JQuery Form helper object.
     private JQFormHelper jqFormHelper;

     // Constructor
     public JQForm(String name) {
         super(name);
     }

     // Initialize the Ajax functionality
     @Override
     public void onInit() {
         super.onInit();
         AjaxControlRegistry.registerAjaxControl(this);
     }

     @Override
     public List getHeadElements() {
         if (headElements == null) {
             headElements = super.getHeadElements();
             getJQueryHelper().addHeadElements(headElements);
         }
         return headElements;
     }

     public JQHelper getJQueryHelper() {
         if (jqHelper == null) {
             jqHelper = new JQFormHelper(this);
         }
         return jqHelper;
     }
 }
Below is an example how to decorate a Form to update itself when the form is submitted: 
 public class FormDemo extends BorderPage {

     private Form form = new Form("form");

     public FormDemo() {

         form.add(new TextField("firstname");
         form.add(new TextField("lastname");
         form.add(new IntegerField("age");

         // Register an Ajax listener on the form which is invoked when the
         // form is submitted.
         form.setActionListener(new AjaxAdapter() {
             public ActionResult onAjaxAction(Control source) {
                 Taconite actionResult = new Taconite();

                 // 1. Replace the Form in the browser with the current one
                 actionResult.replace(form);

                 return actionResult;
             }
         });

         JQFormHelper helper = new JQFormHelper(form);

         // Ajaxify the the Field
         helper.ajaxify();

         addControl(form);
     }
 }

createTemplateModel

protected Map<String,Object> createTemplateModel(Page page,
                                                 Control control,
                                                 Context context)
Description copied from class: JQBehavior
Create a default data model for the Ajax #template.

The following values are added:

  • "context" - the request context path e.g: '/myapp'
  • "#bindings" - the JavaScript bindings for events
  • "#control" - the target control
  • "#selector" - the CSS selector
  • "#event" - the event that initiates the Ajax request
  • "productionMode" - true if Click is running in a production mode (production or profile), false otherwise
  • "url" - the Ajax request URL
  • "JQBehavior.type" - the type of the Ajax request, eg POST or GET
  • "#threshold" - the threshold within which multiple Ajax requests are merged into a single request.
  • "JQBehavior.showBusyIndicator" - flag indicating whether the busy indicator is shown or not
  • "#indicatorOptions" - the Ajax indicator options. Note that #indicatorMessage is rendered as part of the options
  • "#indicatorTarget" - the target element of the Ajax indicator
  • "#errorMessage" - the message to display if an Ajax error occurs
  • "#parameters" - the Ajax request parameters
  • "selector" - the CSS #selector

Overrides:
createTemplateModel in class JQBehavior
Returns:
the default data model for the Ajax template
